What is the average daily activity pattern?

First, with the R command âaggregateâ, Iâm going to calculate the mean of the daily activity pattern and then Iâm going to call the plot function to make the time series.

av_activity <- aggregate(activity$steps, by=list(activity$interval), FUN=mean, na.rm=TRUE)
names(av_activity) <- c("interval", "mean")
plot(av_activity$interval, av_activity$mean, type = "l", col="red", lwd = 2, xlab="Interval", ylab="Average number of steps", main="Average number of steps per intervals")

Now, to answer the question âWhich 5-minute interval, on average across all the days in the dataset, contains the maximum number of steps?â Iâm going to use the new data frame I created âav_activityâ and filter by the mean with the function âwhich.maxâ.

max_interval <- av_activity[which.max(av_activity$mean), ]$interval

So here we can see that the interval 835 contains the maximum number of steps

Imputing missing values

The first thing to do is to calculate the total count of missing values in the data frame, for this, Iâm going to use the sum function with a boolean argument

na_val <- sum(is.na(activity$steps))

From here, we note that the total number of missing values is 2304

Now, as strategy to fill the missing values Iâm going to calculate the mean.

new_steps <- av_activity$mean[match(activity$interval, av_activity$interval)]

The next step is to create the new data set but same as the original but with the new steps calculated above (new_steps)

#Put the new values with the transform function and the ifelse function 
new_activity <- transform(activity, steps = ifelse(is.na(activity$steps),new_steps,
                                                       activity$steps))
#Create the data frame
new_total_steps <- aggregate(steps ~ date, new_activity, sum)
names(new_total_steps) <- c("date", "daily_steps")

Finally, letâs repeat the first question but now with the new data frame. First, the histogram:

hist(new_total_steps$daily_steps, col = "blue", xlab = "Total steps per day", main = "Total number of steps taken each day", breaks = 10)

We can see a slight difference respect to the first histogram. Now, letâs csalculate the median and the mean:

new_mean <- mean(new_total_steps$daily_steps)
new_median <- median(new_total_steps$daily_steps)

From here, we can see that the new mean is 1.076618910^{4} and the new median is 1.076618910^{4}, these are, in fact, different from the first mean and median calculated respectively (9354.2295082,10395). The impact of the missing values here is that decreases both values.

Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?

First, Iâm going to create the new factor variable according to the day, for this Iâm going to use the sapply function with a new one as an argument

#transform the variable
activity$date <- as.Date(strptime(activity$date, format="%Y-%m-%d"))
#Create the new column with the sapply function and a new one 
activity$datetype <- sapply(activity$date, function(x) {
        if (weekdays(x) == "Saturday" | weekdays(x) == "Sunday") 
                {y <- "Weekend"} else 
                {y <- "Weekday"}
                y
        })

Now, letâs create the plot according to the new factor variable with the ggplot function

activity_date <- aggregate(steps~interval + datetype, activity, mean, na.rm = TRUE)
plot<- ggplot(activity_date, aes(x = interval , y = steps, color = datetype)) +
       geom_line() +
       labs(title = "Average daily steps by type of date", x = "Interval", y = "Average number of steps") +
       facet_wrap(~datetype, ncol = 1, nrow=2)
print(plot)
